---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import RelatedTools from "../components/RelatedTools.astro";

const structuredData = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@graph": [
    {
      "@type": "Article",
      headline: "Infant growth chart — WHO weight-for-age and length-for-age",
      url: "https://growthchartcalculator.com/infant-growth-chart/",
      description:
        "A clinical walkthrough of the infant growth chart: WHO weight-for-age and length-for-age percentiles from 0–24 months, how pediatricians read them, and what z-scores add.",
      about: { "@type": "Thing", name: "Infant growth chart" },
      author: { "@type": "Organization", name: "Growth Chart Calculator" },
    },
    {
      "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
      itemListElement: [
        { "@type": "ListItem", position: 1, name: "Home", item: "https://growthchartcalculator.com/" },
        { "@type": "ListItem", position: 2, name: "Infant growth chart", item: "https://growthchartcalculator.com/infant-growth-chart/" },
      ],
    },
  ],
};
---

<Base
  title="Infant Growth Chart — WHO Weight-for-age and Length-for-age (0–24 months)"
  description="Clinical walkthrough of the infant growth chart — WHO weight-for-age and length-for-age percentiles from 0 to 24 months, how pediatricians read them, and how z-scores complement percentiles."
  structuredData={structuredData}
>
  <article class="landing-intro long-form">
    <h2>Infant growth chart</h2>
    <p>
      The infant growth chart most clinicians use from 0 to 24 months is the
      <a href="/who-growth-chart/">WHO Child Growth Standards</a> (2006). The same chart is what
      AAP, NHS, and most national ministries of health recommend for this age range. The version
      for parents is sometimes called the
      <a href="/baby-growth-chart/">"baby growth chart"</a> — it's the same underlying LMS data,
      just with less technical language.
    </p>
    <p>
      To compute your infant's percentile right now, use the
      <a href="/baby-percentile-calculator/"><strong>baby percentile calculator</strong></a>.
      It plots your measurement on the WHO chart and shows both the percentile and the z-score.
    </p>

    <h3>Three infant charts, not one</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Weight-for-age</strong> (WFA) — weight at a given chronological age.</li>
      <li><strong>Length-for-age</strong> (LFA) — recumbent length at a given age.</li>
      <li><strong>Weight-for-length</strong> (WFL) — weight conditional on length, not age. Detects wasting/overweight independent of how old the baby is.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      This site covers WFA and LFA for 0–24 months. WFL is useful for acute malnutrition screening
      and is typically tracked separately in clinical practice.
    </p>

    <h3>Percentiles and z-scores</h3>
    <p>
      Pediatricians read both. A percentile is the rank in the reference distribution (50th = half
      are above, half below). A z-score is the number of standard deviations from the median — it
      keeps being informative past the edges of the chart (below the 3rd or above the 97th) where
      percentile numbers bunch up. The
      <a href="/lms-method/">LMS method</a> is the conversion in both directions.
    </p>

    <h3>Clinical thresholds</h3>
    <p>
      WHO defines &lt;−2 z-score (roughly the 2nd percentile) as the screening threshold for
      moderate underweight or stunting, and &lt;−3 as severe. Above the curve, &gt;+2 WFL flags
      overweight. These thresholds apply to WHO-defined growth failure and don't automatically
      apply to an otherwise-healthy infant who's simply small or large.
    </p>

    <h3>What a single reading means (not much)</h3>
    <p>
      Infants jitter on the chart — they gain unevenly around feeds, illness, teething, and sleep
      regressions. Pediatricians weight <em>trajectory</em> over point-in-time percentile: a baby
      who tracks along the 10th consistently is usually fine; a baby who drops from the 75th to
      the 10th over two visits is the one who gets evaluated.
    </p>

    <h3>Preterm infants use different charts</h3>
    <p>
      For infants born before 37 weeks, the
      <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fenton_growth_chart" rel="noopener">Fenton preterm
      growth chart</a> or Intergrowth-21st is more appropriate, and corrected age (gestational
      adjustment) is used in place of chronological age. WHO term-infant charts understate how
      preterm babies are actually tracking.
    </p>
  </article>

  <RelatedTools
    links={[
      { href: "/baby-percentile-calculator/", title: "Baby Percentile Calculator", description: "Compute percentile + z-score" },
      { href: "/baby-growth-chart/", title: "Baby growth chart", description: "Parent-friendly version" },
      { href: "/who-growth-chart/", title: "WHO Growth Chart", description: "The reference itself" },
      { href: "/lms-method/", title: "LMS method", description: "How the math works" },
      { href: "/weight-for-age/", title: "Weight-for-age", description: "Weight only" },
      { href: "/height-for-age/", title: "Length-for-age", description: "Length only" },
    ]}
  />
</Base>
